title: For Sale:  Springfield Model 1903 30-06 Rock Island Arsenal Bolt Action Rifle made in 1917
location: South Indy---SR 37 and County Line Rd, Indianapolis, Indiana
postcontent:
This is a sporterized Springfield Model 1903 WWI US Army Bolt Action Rifle. 

Produced at the Rock Island Arsenal(Illinois, USA) in 1917. S/N 247XXX.

Beautiful sporterized Monte Carlo hardwood stock, Lymon peep sight with a 1911 patent date. Tons of character and history rolled into this gun.

Markings were removed from the barrel when it was sporterized(barrel measures 23-1/4" from receiver to tip). Markings are present and crystal clear on the receiver. Bolt has a stainless finish. Front sight appears to be original design.

Should be inspected by a competent gunsmith prior to use to verify safety and function. It is one of over a million "low serial number" Model 1903's that have been the subject of on-going debate since WWI regarding the single heat-treating method used to produce the receivers. They are regarded by some as "unsafe to fire" due to incidents during WW1 with fractured receivers and injuries.

Heat treating methods were primitive in the US in the early 20th century and relied on the gunsmith to "eyeball" the metal to guess temperature. The result was some receivers that were overheated and became brittle. Combined with bad shell casings or overpressured ammo, the brittle metal receivers exploded like glass on firing. The result was lost eyes and facial injuries.

Out of 1 million guns, 100 or so failed during WWI. Some of those failures resulted from American soldiers sticking captured German 8mm(.32 caliber) rounds into these (.30 caliber) rifles. 

These guns have been the subject of debate since then, with many saying "never fire them", and others using them heavily.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Vzor45 .25 cal
postcontent:
1 Vzor 45 


(3) 8Rd Magazine


1 IWB Black Reversible Holster W/Extra Mag Pouch 








BEAUTIFUL COLLECTORS PIECE




ONLY CARRIED BY HIGH RANKING (DDR) OFFICERS AS BUG & STATUS SYMBOL




MID 5 DIGIT SERIAL # 




CLEAN RIFILING 




WORKS PERFECTLY 







The Vzor 45, commonly known as CZ 45 is a compact  blowback operated   semi-automatic pistol  chambered in  .25 ACP . It was made in  Czechoslovakia  and later in the  Czech Republic . Derived from the CZ-36 following World War II, the CZ-45 is currently manufactured by  Česká zbrojovka Uherský Brod  as the CZ-92.

In 1945 the CZ-36 was redesigned by Jan Kratochvil to make it easier (hence cheaper) to manufacture and became the Vzor 45 (model 1945) but is generally known as CZ-45. The safety lever which had sometimes appeared on the CZ-36 was eliminated (though a few early model 45s were manufactured with a safety lever). The changes included the addition of a side plate to simplify assembly and a magazine safety. The CZ-36 had a connector from the trigger to the hammer that ran on the left side of the magazine, whereas the CZ-45 has a Browning style stirrup-shaped connector that runs on both sides of the magazine.

The overall design of the receiver, slide, guide rod, and recoil spring are very similar to the earlier Browning .25 design. The barrel mount is also like the Browning, with a single lug that rotates into a slot in the frame. The trigger pivots on a pin.

When the trigger is activated and the hammer is down, the connector is pulled forward, rotating the hammer backward into cocked position. When the hammer reaches full cock, it is freed to fall and strike the  firing pin , which ignites the cartridge. The hammer is not cocked by the slide--technically speaking, this is a self-loading repeating pistol, not an automatic or semi-automatic. Other than the heavy double-action trigger pull, the only safety mechanism is the magazine safety. When the magazine is inserted, it moves a bar which allows the connector to engage the sear. When the magazine is removed from the gun, the bar disconnects the trigger from the sear.

Disassembly is similar to the Browning. Remove the magazine and make sure the chamber is empty. Draw the slide back about 1 centimeter and rotate the barrel clockwise a quarter-turn. Remove the barrel and slide forward off the receiver. Other than the guide rod and recoil spring, there are no small parts that come loose.

The CZ-45 holds 8 rounds in the magazine and has a simple groove down the top of the slide for sighting. Its great merits are its simplicity and reliability, ease of field-stripping, and accuracy--despite its primitive sighting groove and double action only trigger.
